ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Have you established a sleep pattern for your infant or does your infant sleep on his/her own schedule?
Notes: 1= Established a sleep pattern; 2= Sleeps on his/her own schedule; 999= Decline to answer

ElementDescription: How many mornings per week does your infant wake up on his/her own?
How many mornings per week is your infant awakened by a caretaker?
By how much does your child's bedtime and wake up time change from night to night?
Notes: 1= Less than 15 minutes; 2= 15 to 30 minutes; 3= 30 to 60 minutes; 4= More than 60 minutes; 999= Decline to answer

How does your baby fall asleep? While feeding?
How does your baby fall asleep? Being rocked?
How does your baby fall asleep? Being held?
How does your baby fall asleep? In bed alone?
How does your baby fall asleep? In bed near parent?

How much time does your child spend in sleep during the NIGHT (between 7 in the evening and 7 in the morning) in hours and minutes?
How much time does your child spend in sleep during the DAY (between 7 in the morning and 7 in the evening) in hours and minutes?
Approximately how many hours is your infant's longest sleep period during the day or night?

What is the average length of the naps in minutes?
Does your infant's sleep pattern vary from day to day?
Is your infant's sleep pattern regular and predictable?

ElementDescription: What is your infant's preferred sleeping position?
Notes: 1= Back; 2= Side; 3= Stomach; 4= It varies; 999= Decline to answer

Notes: last night: number of night time wakenings

ElementDescription: Does your child sleep in the same room as you?
Average number of night wakings per night:

Do you consider your child's sleep as a problem?

ElementDescription: Has your child ever been given over-the-counter or prescription medications at bedtime that help him/her calm down and/or fall asleep?
If yes, please list the medication.
Dosage:

Notes: 1= Always; 2= Often; 3= Sometimes; 4= Rarely; 5= Never; 999= Decline to answer

ElementDescription: When your baby sleeps alone, is his/her crib or bed in the same room where you sleep?

How did your new baby usually sleep in the past 2 weeks? On a twin or larger mattress or bed
How did your new baby usually sleep in the past 2 weeks? On a couch, sofa, or armchair
How did your new baby usually sleep in the past 2 weeks? In an infant car seat or swing
How did your new baby usually sleep in the past 2 weeks? In a sleeping sack or wearable blanket
How did your new baby usually sleep in the past 2 weeks? With a blanket
How did your new baby usually sleep in the past 2 weeks? With toys, cushions, or pillows, including nursing pillows

Does your baby use a pacifier during sleep?
Over the past two weeks: What time do you usually start your child''s bedtime routine (start getting your child ready for bed)? Example would be written as 7:45pm.
In a typical week, how often does your child have the exact same bedtime routine?

Notes: 1=Crib; 2=Own bed; 3=Parents'' bed; 4=Co-sleeper (attached to parents'' bed); 5=Bassinet/infant seat; 6=Swing/stroller; 7=Parent''s/adult''s arms; 8= Other

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: How does your child usually fall asleep at bedtime?
Notes: 1=While being held or rocked; 2=With an adult in the room, but not being held or rocked; 3=On own (without an adult in the room)

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: At bedtime, does your child usually fall asleep while breastfeeding, bottle feeding, or drinking from a sippy cup?
What time do you usually put your child to bed at night? (time of turning out the light.)
Typically, how difficult is bedtime for your child, for example, fussing, crying, protesting?
Notes: 0= Very easy;1= Somewhat easy; 2= Neither easy nor difficult; 3= Somewhat difficult; 4= Very difficult

ElementDescription: How long does it take to put your baby to sleep in the evening?
Notes: Hours and Minutes combined into a decimal

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: Where does your child sleep most of the time? (CHECK ONE) - Selected Choice
Notes: 0= In his/her own room; 1= In parents' room; 2= In sibling or other's room;  3= In another room of the house;  4= Other, please specify

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: Where does your child sleep for most of the night?
Notes: 1=Crib; 2=Own bed (any size); 3=Parents'' bed; 4=Co-sleeper (attached to parents'' bed); 5=Bassinet/infant seat; 6=Swing/stroller; 7=Other

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: How many times does your child usually wake during the night?
Over the past two weeks: When your child wakes up during the night, what do you usually do?
Notes: 1=Pick up my child and put him/her back down while still awake; 2=Bottle feed or give a sip cup to put my child back to sleep; 3=Breastfeed/nurse my child back to sleep; 4=Play with my child, watch TV, or use/show smartphone/tablet; 5=None of these

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: How much total time during the NIGHT is your child usually awake (between when your child goes to bed and wakes for the day)? Example: If your child wakes up 2 times and is awake for about 15 minutes each time, your child''s total time spent awake is 30 minutes. In that case, write 0 hours, 30 minutes.
On a typical night, what is the longest stretch of time that your child is asleep during the night without waking up? Minutes
Over the past two weeks: What time does your child wake up in the morning?

Over the past two weeks: How much total time does your child spend sleeping during the NIGHT (between when your child goes to bed and wakes for the day)? Example: If your child sleeps for 3 hours, wakes up, then sleeps for 5 hours and 30 minutes more, your child sleeps for 8 hours and 30 minutes total
Please rate how well your child usually sleeps at night: (CHECK ONE)
Notes: 0= Very well;  1= Well; 2= Fairly well; 3= Fairly poorly; 4= Poorly; 5= Very poorly

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: On a typical DAY, how many naps does your child take (between when your child wakes for the day and goes to bed at night)?

Over the past two weeks: How much total time does your child spend sleeping during the DAY (between when your child wakes for the day and goes to bed at night)? Example: If your child took 2 naps and slept 1 hour each time, your child''s total time spent sleeping during the day is 2 hours
What is your relationship to this child?
Notes: 1= Biological Mother; 2= Biological Father; 3= Grandmother; 4= Grandfather; 5= Other; 6= Mother; 7= Father; 8= Grandparent; 999= Decline to answer

ElementDescription: Over the past two weeks: Do you consider your child''s sleep a problem?
Notes: 1=Not a problem at all; 2=A very small problem; 3=A small problem; 4=A moderate problem; 5=A serious problem

ElementDescription: What is the highest level of education you have completed?
Notes: 1 = Less than high school; 2 = High School/GED; 3 = Some college or trade school; 4 = College degree; 5 = Post-college degree (MA, professional degree, PhD); 6 = Refused; 9=Missing; 888=Prefer not to answer
